<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-975-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 975 020.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 18 1989 n279 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Users spur mgm't advance. (network management) (Spectrum ConceptsInc. developing new network software-distribution capability)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schultz, Beth; Rockwell, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Spectrum Concepts Inc is developing a new networksoftware-distribution capability based on its XCOM 6.2file-transfer product.andP;  The company is responding to the needs ofusers, many of whom have built their own software-distributionsystems on top of XCOM.andP;  Spectrum officials say that the sheernumber of microcomputers in use and loose organization of LANenvironments is resulting in demand for products that providenetwork control.andP;  Industry analysts predict a boom insoftware-distribution systems in 1990 and 1991.andP;  Distributionacross multivendor environments is a major issue for some users;Spectrum's XCOM is compatible with IBM's Logical Unit 6.2 and withnative OS/2, DEC VAX, and Unix systems.andP;  The new XCOMsoftware-distribution system will be available by mid-1990 andwill be able to distribute files and programs across a networkfrom a host mainframe.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Spectrum Concepts Inc. (product development).andO;Product:   XCOM 6.2 (Communications software) (usage).andO;Topic:     Wide Area NetworksNetwork Management SoftwareProduct DevelopmentDistribution ManagementFile Transfer.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>